Hi Dr. Krutz,

Happy to answer these questions!


 1.
What has been your biggest challenge when working with a team?

Communication is easily the biggest challenge. At first, it was incredibly =
hard to communicate with my team, but as time went on, we became used to ea=
ch other.

 2.
What is something you feel has gone very well to bridge the communication g=
ap between Deaf/hard-of-hearing and non-hard-of-hearing students?

This is a really hard question. Generally, we just need exposure. Both side=
s need to be willing to communicate. And sometimes, a student just isn't a =
good student, which reflects badly on one side. Feeling a connection (for e=
xample, becoming friends) is really helpful. Get to know the other person. =
Do team-building exercises.

 3.
In general, what have your experiences been like working on teams in Softwa=
rer Engineering classes?

Both bad and good. I sort of became the team leader in my group, so I got l=
istened to quite often. Communication becomes a lot less of a problem when =
you're the leader!

 4.
What recommendations would you have for other deaf students working as part=
 of a software team?

I would say participate and communicate a lot. Take a leadership role! This=
 is actually no different than a non-deaf person, but when there's a mixtur=
e of hearing and deaf students, communication is even more important. A mix=
ture multiplies communication problems, so it's super-important to communic=
ate well.

Taking a leadership role means not just sitting there and expecting others =
to do the work. This is very hard in a classroom environment, unfortunately=
, but it needs to be done.

 5.
What services (NTID/RIT student services), if any, do you utilize when part=
icipating in team work?

I sometimes used an interpreter. I was very lucky to be able to actually un=
derstand my team members for the most part. With other team members, I woul=
d not have been so lucky.

